    "narrative": "The offensive ceiling for Ghost Ride the WHIP today rests on a trio of high-efficiency starts against favorable matchups. **Jazz Chisholm Jr.** (76.59) headlines our output, as he faces McCullers Jr. in a setup that maximizes his specific elite-speed profile; the combination of a high xERA and McCullers Jr.'s slow delivery to the plate creates a perfect storm for **Jazz Chisholm Jr.** to capitalize on the scarcest category, stolen bases. Similarly, **James Wood** (75.23) is a priority play batting leadoff against Hudson, B. His score is bolstered by a commanding 19% SP skill advantage and the prime opportunity afforded by the leadoff spot to catalyze our counting stats. **Trevor Story** (73.82) also demands attention, as he draws a significantly favorable park factor (+16%) that elevates his raw projection, making him our highest-scoring UTIL play despite the neutral platoon stance.\n\nWhile **Mickey Moniak** (63.92) is a mandatory start due to his leadoff duties and a robust 14% platoon advantage against Peralta, F, we must be cautious with the lower-scoring end of our roster. **Brice Turang** (48.20) and **Alex Freeland** (49.29) hover dangerously close to our \"Below Floor\" threshold. **Brice Turang** faces a significant test against Skenes, whose elite profile (-19% SP skill adjustment) and the threat of a high-end catcher\u2019s pop time (1.89s) severely dampen the base projection for a speed-reliant player. Our most difficult bench decision involved **Seiya Suzuki** (44.34), who was the first cut from the starting nine. While his projected efficiency exceeded our 40.0 floor, the optimizer opted for the higher matchup upside provided by **Jose Caballero** and **Tyler Soderstrom**, as **Seiya Suzuki** was penalized for lingering uncertainty regarding his spot in the batting order and a difficult matchup against the effective Sheehan. We remain wary of **Brice Turang** and **Alex Freeland** today; should the early innings confirm Skenes\u2019 dominance, we will look to minimize plate appearance leakage to protect our cumulative game caps.",
